<question>  
A perovskite slab model consisting of 8 PbI$_6^{4-}$ octahedra interacts with organic cations at the surface. Density Functional Theory calculations find the binding energy of a single organic cation with one PbI$_6$ octahedron to be –0.85 eV. Given that adding an additional cation increases PbI$_6$ octahedral distortion by 2.5%, decreasing binding energy by 0.12 eV per octahedron distorted, calculate the net binding energy (in eV) if 3 organic cations sequentially passivate the slab, distorting all 8 octahedra cumulatively. Assume binding energy reductions accumulate linearly with distortion and only distortions caused by these 3 cations affect binding energy.</question>

<question>  
Within a quantum confined lead iodide perovskite nanocrystal, the bandgap widens due to spatial confinement. Given the effective mass of the electron $m_e^* = 0.12 m_0$ and the hole $m_h^* = 0.15 m_0$, where $m_0$ is the free electron mass, calculate the increase in bandgap energy (in eV) for a spherical nanocrystal of radius 3 nm. Use the effective mass approximation and the particle-in-a-sphere model, applying the formula:  
$$ \Delta E = \frac{\hbar^2 \pi^2}{2 R^2} \left(\frac{1}{m_e^*} + \frac{1}{m_h^*}\right) $$  
where $\hbar = 1.055 \times 10^{-34}$ J·s, and $1\, \text{eV} = 1.602 \times 10^{-19}$ J.</question>

<question>  
An organic ammonium cation with formula C$_6$H$_{16}$N$^{+}$ is proposed as a surface passivator for PbI$_6^{4-}$ octahedra in a perovskite. Using Density Derived Electrostatic and Chemical (DDEC) charges, the effective cation number defined as the net positive charge that contributes to electrostatic stabilization is 0.78 per ammonium function. If the structure contains 12 such cations balanced with 16 PbI$_6^{4-}$ octahedra, calculate the overall charge imbalance per formula unit and suggest which IUPAC name corresponds to the cation given the molecular formula.</question>

<question>  
Consider an organic cation passivating a PbI$_6^{4-}$ surface through hydrogen bonding, modeled by DFT calculations as having a binding energy of –1.4 eV per cation. Upon substitution of the terminal amine group by a methyl group, the binding energy decreases by 35%. Calculate the new binding energy in kJ·mol$^{-1}$ (1 eV = 96.485 kJ·mol$^{-1}$). Round to two decimal places.</question>

<question>  
Using Density Functional Theory, the shift in electrostatic potential induced by an organic cation at a perovskite surface is calculated as +0.42 V relative to vacuum. If the cation insertion reduces the work function of the substrate from 5.25 eV to 4.83 eV, calculate the dipole moment per unit area (in Debye·nm$^{-2}$), considering the Helmholtz equation:  
$$ \Delta \phi = \frac{e \mu}{\varepsilon_0 A} $$  
where $\Delta \phi$ is the potential shift, $e = 1.602 \times 10^{-19}$ C, $\varepsilon_0 = 8.854 \times 10^{-12}$ C$^2$·J$^{-1}$·m$^{-1}$, $A$ is the unit area of 1 nm$^{2}$, and $1\, \text{Debye} = 3.336 \times 10^{-30}$ C·m.</question>
